<b>Alan H. Fishman</b> (born 16 March 1946 <ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>) was the last CEO of <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../261/214261.xml">
Washington Mutual</link></company>
 (WaMu) before its seizure by federal regulators on <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../203/28203.xml">
September 25</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../825/35825.xml">
2008</link>.  Most of the company, including its banking operations, was sold to <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../001/231001.xml">
JPMorgan Chase</link></company>
 for $1.836 billion. Fishman joined WaMu on <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../488/28488.xml">
8 September</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../825/35825.xml">
2008</link>, replacing outgoing CEO <physical_entity wordnetid="100001930" confidence="0.8">
<executive wordnetid="110069645" confidence="0.8">
<person wordnetid="100007846" confidence="0.8">
<leader wordnetid="109623038" confidence="0.8">
<administrator wordnetid="109770949" confidence="0.8">
<causal_agent wordnetid="100007347" confidence="0.8">
<head wordnetid="110162991" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../138/4005138.xml">
Kerry Killinger</link></head>
</causal_agent>
</administrator>
</leader>
</person>
</executive>
</physical_entity>
 as part of that bank's restructuring in the face of the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../100/10062100.xml">
subprime mortgage crisis</link> of 2008.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> <p>

According to C-Span on <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../178/28178.xml">
26 September</link> <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../825/35825.xml">
2008</link>, Alan H. Fishman was ultimately paid $19 million dollars for three weeks of being with Washington Mutual, including severance pay.  Meanwhile, the company's stock price dwindled to only pennies.  The previous CEO was paid $14 million for one year on the job.</p>
<p>

Fishman holds a bachelor's degree from <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../157/4157.xml">
Brown University</link></university>
 and a master's degree in economics from <university wordnetid="108286163" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<ranking wordnetid="114429484" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../310/6310.xml">
Columbia University</link></ranking>
</university>
. He was previously president and chief operating officer of <slope wordnetid="109437454" confidence="0.8">
<company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.8">
<geological_formation wordnetid="109287968" confidence="0.8">
<bank wordnetid="109213565" confidence="0.8">
<institution wordnetid="108053576" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../259/5567259.xml">
Sovereign Bank</link></institution>
</bank>
</geological_formation>
</company>
</slope>
 and president and chief executive officer of <link>
Independence Community Bank</link>. He has served as chairman of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../016/19476016.xml">
Meridian Capital Group</link> (beginning in 2007), one of the nation's largest commercial mortgage brokerage firms. He has been a private equity investor, focusing on financial services at <link>
Neuberger &amp; Berman</link>, <link>
Adler &amp; Shaykin</link> and at his own firm <link>
Columbia Financial Partners</link>. In addition, he held senior executive positions at <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../000/231000.xml">
Chemical Bank</link> and <company wordnetid="108058098" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../064/4327064.xml">
ContiFinancial Corporation</link></company>
. <ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref></p>
